&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from [bold]the Association o[bold]f Bikeability Schemes[bold] (CYS0120)[bold]THE ASSOCIATION OF BIKEABILITY SCHEMES
[normal]1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]About TABS[bold]1.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]TABS is a trade association which works with
[normal] the Department for Transport to ensure the highest quality of delivery of Bikeability cycle training. TABS aims to work in the interest of Bikeability schemes, and represents the view of the professional cycle training industry in discussions and decision
[normal]-making activities with Government agencies and other public bodies. TABS’s ultimate aim is more people taking trips by bike more often and more safely.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chris Boardman submitted a statement expressing the support of the work that TABS is doing: 
[normal]“Cycling 
[normal]has never been more important than now in terms of promoting enjoyable physical activity.  Being able to ride a bike confidently on road, with minimum risk, is an essential life skill for an active and healthy lifestyle. Bikeability has an important role t
[normal]o play in giving people of all ages, especially the next generation of young people and their parents, the skills and confidence to make everyday trips by bike. If we want to transform cycling in this country we need to do all we can to make a difference a
[normal]nd make sure that the government is taking us seriously.
[normal]I welcome the role of TABS in making the case for the continued funding for Bikeability beyond the term of this current government.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]TABS has been delivering courses across the sector aiming to ensu
[normal]re the consistency of the quality delivery of cycle training on behalf of the Department for Transport. This seminar is based on principles of 
[normal]Road Danger Reduction
[normal], which aim to promote benign active travel and reduce t
[normal]he source of road danger. We are submitting a number of case studies which give an overview of work in this area, especially around training drivers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Training people who ride bicycles[bold]2.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Why train cyclists? Surely anyone can ride a bike? Ideally the spaces w
[normal]here people live, work and shop should be accessible on foot and on bike without any special training, and this is largely the case. The majority of people who cycle manage perfectly well with little guidance and statistically, riding a bike is a low risk 
[normal]activity per mile travelled. There are, however, many people who perceive cycling as more risky than it is, people who would cycle if they had help with gaining the skills and confidence to do so. Training  these people helps them make the transition from 
[normal]someone who is reluctant to ride due to perceived risk to some who can ride anywhere with confidence in a short time. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal](One argument for separating people on bikes from people in cars is that many more people would take to cycling on road after a 
[normal]few mont
[normal]hs
[normal] of experience riding in a 
[normal]segregated environment. People who undergo cycle training can make this transition in 2-4 hours!)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Even confident people who already cycle can benefit from training. As with any activity input from an expert can increase effici
[normal]ency thereby improving the enjoyment of cycling, perhaps increase peoples speed (by encouraging them to ride as part of the traffic flow) and definitely ensuring that what is a relatively low risk activity becomes even less risky.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]People who cycle are mor
[normal]e likely to ride their bikes more often, make longer trips and cycle in all seasons as evidenced in 
[normal] research
[normal] commissioned by Transport for London in 2003.
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Training people who drive to be aware of cyclists[bold]3.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Some Bikeability schemes
[normal] in London were delivering cyclists/driver awareness sessions  since 2007. These sessions were largely theoretical, classroom-based sessions. They were delivered to all people who drove for some London councils on council business. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Following the success 
[normal]of this scheme, Bikeability schemes were commissioned to develop a programme whereby lorry drivers, contracted by the councils, received on bike training in addition to a theory session. (This anecdotally fostered much empathy between some council’s driver
[normal]s and local cyclists). This programme was replicated with bus companies (Abellio, Stagecoach and Go Ahead) who also agreed to go one step further and training bus driver trainers as cycling instructors in order to deliver this more sustainably in-house.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Encouraged by the success of the driver training TFL, in partnership with Bikeability schemes, developed an on-bike driver/cyclist awareness course that met HGV/PCV 
[normal]CPC
[normal] outcomes. These courses were submitted to JAUPT, the CPC accrediting body by  Transport for London. Out of this came the Safe Urban Driving course (SUD) which is being promoted to many professional drivers who use London’s roads through the Freight 
[normal]Operators Recognition Scheme (FORS).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal] The one day training SUD course comprises of a practical and a theory module and contributes 7 hours towards the legal CPC requirement of 35 hours of professional training for drivers. The aims of this course are:
[normal]●
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]to 
[normal]ensure passenger comfort and safety
[normal]●
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To know the social environment of road transport
[normal]●
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To make drivers aware of the risks of the road
[normal]●
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]to adopt behaviour to help enhance the image of the company
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]An outcome of the development of this training has been interes
[normal]t from professional drivers who are not required to undergo CPC training in particular the private can hire company Addison Lee who piloted this training for 20 drivers then trained their own trainers to deliver this on bike driver/cyclists awareness train
[normal]ing in-house.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Making cycle training a prerequisite of driver training may lead to better and more responsible drivers as well as drivers who can cycle and may feel happy about making some trips by bike rather than in a car. We are looking forward to input
[normal]ting to the proposed Green Paper on young driver training 
[normal]&#xa0;
