[normal]4.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recommendations [bold]4.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Active promotion of cycling:[bold] While we are sure many submis
[normal]sions to the select committee will highlight the need to redesign the road environment helping to reduce the risk and the perception of risk, we believe cheaper immediate wins could be achieved by positive marketing of cycling as desirable low risk benign 
[normal]activity that anyone can do.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Create a road sharing environment:[bold] Bikeability and National Standard cycle training gives people on bikes the skills to share the road with people in motor vehicles by communicating to them through looking and road positioning
[normal]. Ensuring that the speed differential between modes is low would encourage riders to move within the flow of traffic and discourage drivers from ‘punishing’ people on bikes using aggressive behaviour when the driver perceives the cyclists as ‘in their way
[normal]’. 20mph (or lower) speed limits in all urban areas, enforced through design and policing would help people share the road space
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Funding and promotion of adult cycle training[bold]: rebranding it to remove the child-centred stigma attached (Urban riding skills 
[normal]training perhaps?) would help adults make the transition from off road leisure riders to everyday cyclists in a short time. T
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Continued funding and promotion of Bikeability for young people:[bold] through the Bikeability schemes and Youth Sports Trusts. Such fu
[normal]nding should be guaranteed across terms of government. Up-skilling people of all ages through training as well as messages about how to road share will minimise risk on the roads
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Funding and promotion of on-bike driver training[bold]: While this has been happen
[normal]ing for too short a time to accrue more than anecdotal evidence of the value of getting drivers on bikes there is definitely a case from the small amount of feedback received from participants (TfL have this data) to recommend that this scheme be scaled up
[normal] nationally and that anyone who drives a lorry or a bus on roads where people ride bikes should get such training. The training should also be rolled-out to all professional drivers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Cycle training for anyone who a gets a driving licence[bold]: If, as a society
[normal] we seriously wish to normalise cycling and minimise road risk, demonstrating the ability to ride on road and understand the basics of the highway code should be demonstrated on a bicycle before people are allowed a provisional driving licence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]TABS welco
[normal]mes 
[normal]The Transport Committee inquiry on cycling safety [bold]and looks forward to the renewed focus on cycling both in parliament and the media. We would be happy to contribute further by submitting additional evidence as required.
